Aspirants in Kirinyaga county have promised to promote peace in their campaigns as the election nears. They also said they will adhere to electoral laws and all the guidelines they receive from the Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission. They made the promise on Thursday in Kerugoya, where they met with IEBC officials. IEBC Ndia constituency coordinator John Njogu lauded the aspirants for agreeing to adhere to the terms laid down by the commission. He also praised them for their willingness to uphold peace during the campaign season. The aspirants said the meeting was an eye-opener for many of them, particularly first-time contenders. Eliud Wanjau, the running mate of Kirinyaga governor aspirant Wangui Ngirici, praised the IEBC for observing the timelines for the submission of different documents by the aspirants. "The IEBC enlightened us on the calendar of events and the deadlines of submitting our papers. We are appreciative of their concern and their patience towards all the aspirants,‚Äù he said. UDA nominee for woman representative seat, Jane Njeri, lauded the commission for conducting civic education. Former county speaker Ann Wangechi, an independent candidate for the county woman representative position, commended the commission for its efforts to curb hooliganism at political rallies. She urged the youth to avoid being misused by selfish politicians to disrupt rallies.